      "content": "i see. so basically, because of his background, the person in Case B is actually judged more harshly because they're seen as a higher risk to society? it almost sounds like his zip code and employment status basically negate any chance for a rehabilitative sentence compared to someone like Case A. do you think a judge would ever see \"sporadic employment\" as a sign that someone needs *more* support and rehab, or is it almost always automatically treated as a red flag for future crime?",
